<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">to any other.  The Village was now in an uproar the women taken up their hidden stores for the fair.  In the fall after the <span class="AddHand-author">harvest</span> the grain is deposited in pits which are about eight feet deep the mou<span class="DelHand-author">g</span><span class="AddHand-author">t</span>h large enough to admit a person while the <span class="DelHand-author">h</span><span class="AddHand-author">i</span>nside is hollowed to any size required and lined with St<span class="AddHand-author">r</span>aw.  The grain thrown in will keep for years.  Having nothing to do and being heartly disgusted with the inhabitants of this Village we took our departure for the lower Village where and along the road we observed all hands busily employed for the expedition.  It was surprising to see the quantity of grain which these people have to spare.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">This afternoon I went to see the remains of a number of Sioux that were killed <span class="AddHand-author">several</span> years ago.  Some say the number exceeds Three hundred.  This V<span class="AddHand-author">i</span>llages were united in this affair. <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>hey surrounded the enemy surprised their wives made many prisoners, drove many into the Missisouri and but few got home.  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>his severe</p>
